{
  "texts": [
    "This argument, developed over this and several other articles (Ford, 2014 (Ford,, 2015; see also Steward, 2000; Hornsby, 2004; Lavin, 2013 Lavin,, 2015;; Valaris, 2015) is echoed by the case made above (in §4).",
    "As Ford notes, the logic of the Davidsonian A-D Principle is compelling here: if the action is identical with some independently specifiable movement, these must at least include those of the body; but if they include more than the body, then the body's movements considered alone are not the action.",
    "Many action theorists, Davidson prominent among them, have found this latter claim unacceptable and have been forced from it to the Strict Bodily Constraint.",
    "This suggests that it is the underlying principle in Davidson 's argument that must be rejected if we want to endorse the claim that actions can be environmentally constituted.",
    "Tellingly, Ford's (2018) own 'materialist' solution, which involves the claim that actions extend beyond the body, is set within the contemporary Anscombean framework that this paper recommends to HEC's defenders."
  ]
}